1️⃣ JOINS – Questions & Answers
True/False (20)

INNER JOIN returns only matching rows. (True)

LEFT JOIN returns all rows from the left table. (True)

RIGHT JOIN returns all rows from the right table. (True)

FULL OUTER JOIN returns all rows from both tables. (True)

CROSS JOIN returns the Cartesian product of two tables. (True)

SELF JOIN joins a table to itself. (True)

NATURAL JOIN automatically joins columns with the same name. (True)

INNER JOIN includes unmatched rows. (False)

LEFT JOIN can return NULLs in the left table. (False)

RIGHT JOIN can return NULLs in the right table. (False)

CROSS JOIN always returns fewer rows than INNER JOIN. (False)

SELF JOIN is useful to compare rows within a table. (True)

FULL OUTER JOIN is a combination of LEFT and RIGHT JOIN. (True)

NATURAL JOIN requires manual specification of columns. (False)

LEFT JOIN and RIGHT JOIN always return the same results. (False)

CROSS JOIN can produce a very large number of rows. (True)

INNER JOIN requires a common column to match rows. (True)

SELF JOIN can use alias names for the same table. (True)

LEFT JOIN can include rows with no matches in the right table. (True)

CROSS JOIN automatically filters unmatched rows. (False)

Gap Filling (20)

An _______ JOIN returns only matching rows. → INNER

_______ JOIN returns all rows from the left table. → LEFT

_______ JOIN returns all rows from the right table. → RIGHT

_______ JOIN returns all rows from both tables. → FULL OUTER

_______ JOIN produces a Cartesian product. → CROSS

A table joined to itself uses _______ JOIN. → SELF

NATURAL JOIN automatically uses _______ columns. → common/same name

INNER JOIN requires _______ columns in both tables. → matching

LEFT JOIN can include _______ values from the right table. → NULL

RIGHT JOIN can include _______ values from the left table. → NULL

CROSS JOIN multiplies the number of rows of two tables to form the _______ product. → Cartesian

SELF JOIN often uses _______ for table aliases. → alias

FULL OUTER JOIN can be simulated using _______ JOIN with UNION. → LEFT and RIGHT

NATURAL JOIN cannot be used if there are no _______ column names. → same

INNER JOIN ignores _______ rows. → unmatched

CROSS JOIN has _______ conditions. → no matching

LEFT JOIN includes all rows from the _______ table. → left

RIGHT JOIN includes all rows from the _______ table. → right

SELF JOIN is useful for _______ relationships. → hierarchical or comparative

FULL OUTER JOIN returns NULLs for _______ columns. → unmatched

Short Answer (10)

Define INNER JOIN. → Returns only rows with matching values in both tables.

Define LEFT JOIN. → Returns all rows from the left table and matched rows from the right.

Define RIGHT JOIN. → Returns all rows from the right table and matched rows from the left.

Define FULL OUTER JOIN. → Returns all rows from both tables; unmatched columns appear as NULL.

What is CROSS JOIN? → Produces Cartesian product of two tables.

What is SELF JOIN? → A table joined to itself using alias names.

What is NATURAL JOIN? → Automatically joins columns with the same name.

Why use JOINs? → To combine data from multiple tables in a single query.

Difference between INNER JOIN and LEFT JOIN? → INNER returns only matching rows; LEFT returns all left rows even if no match.

Give a practical example where CROSS JOIN is useful. → Generating all possible combinations, e.g., students × courses.









2️⃣ CHARACTER MANIPULATION – Questions & Answers
True/False (20)

UPPER() converts text to uppercase. (True)

LOWER() converts text to lowercase. (True)

LIKE is used for pattern matching. (True)

_ matches exactly one character. (True)

% matches zero or more characters. (True)

% matches exactly one character. (False)

_ matches zero or more characters. (False)

Character functions can be used in WHERE clauses. (True)

LIKE is case-sensitive in most databases. (True/False depends on DB)

UPPER() is used to make searches case-insensitive. (True)

CONCAT() can combine two text strings. (True)

LENGTH() returns the length of text. (True)

TRIM() removes extra spaces from text. (True)

REPLACE() can replace part of a string. (True)

SUBSTRING() extracts part of a string. (True)

UPPER() modifies the original table permanently. (False)

LOWER() can be combined with LIKE for searches. (True)

_ and % can be used together in LIKE patterns. (True)

Character manipulation is only for numeric columns. (False)

Pattern matching cannot be used in ORDER BY. (False)

Gap Filling (20)

_______ converts text to uppercase. → UPPER

_______ converts text to lowercase. → LOWER

_______ is used for pattern matching. → LIKE

_ matches _______ character(s). → exactly one

% matches _______ character(s). → zero or more

CONCAT() is used to _______ strings. → combine

LENGTH() returns the _______ of text. → length

TRIM() is used to remove _______. → extra spaces

REPLACE() is used to _______ a substring. → replace

SUBSTRING() is used to _______ part of a string. → extract

LIKE patterns can include _______ and _______ wildcards. → %,_

UPPER() is often used to make searches _______. → case-insensitive

LOWER() is used for _______ comparison. → uniform

Pattern matching is used in _______ clauses. → WHERE

%abc% matches strings that _______ contain ‘abc’. → anywhere

_abc matches strings where ‘abc’ is _______ character(s) after the first. → immediately after one

CONCAT(first, last) joins first and last names into one _______. → string

TRIM() can remove spaces from _______ or _______. → left, right

REPLACE(text, ‘a’, ‘b’) changes all ‘a’ to _______. → ‘b’

LIKE is commonly used for _______ filtering. → text

Short Answer (10)

What does UPPER() do? → Converts text to uppercase.

What does LOWER() do? → Converts text to lowercase.

Difference between _ and % in LIKE? → _ matches 1 char, % matches 0 or more.

What is CONCAT()? → Combines two or more strings into one.

Purpose of LENGTH()? → Returns the number of characters in a string.

What does TRIM() do? → Removes spaces from left/right of text.

How does REPLACE() work? → Replaces a substring with another substring.

How is SUBSTRING() used? → Extracts part of a string based on position and length.

Why combine UPPER() with LIKE? → To make searches case-insensitive.

What is pattern matching? → Searching for text using wildcards % and _.







3️⃣ AGGREGATE FUNCTIONS – Questions & Answers
True/False (20)

COUNT counts rows in a table or group. (True)

SUM calculates the total of numeric values. (True)

AVG calculates the average of numeric values. (True)

MIN returns the smallest value. (True)

MAX returns the largest value. (True)

GROUP BY is used with aggregate functions. (True)

HAVING filters after grouping. (True)

WHERE filters groups. (False)

Aggregate functions return one value per group. (True)

COUNT(*) counts only non-null values. (False)

SUM can include nulls automatically. (False)

AVG ignores null values. (True)

MIN ignores null values. (True)

MAX ignores null values. (True)

GROUP BY can have multiple columns. (True)

HAVING can filter on aggregates like SUM or AVG. (True)

COUNT(column) counts non-null values only. (True)

Aggregate functions cannot be used in SELECT. (False)

ORDER BY can sort grouped results. (True)

Aggregate functions are not used for summary reports. (False)

Gap Filling (20)

_______ counts rows. → COUNT

_______ calculates the total of numeric values. → SUM

_______ calculates average. → AVG

_______ returns minimum value. → MIN

_______ returns maximum value. → MAX

_______ groups rows with same values. → GROUP BY

_______ filters grouped results. → HAVING

WHERE filters _______ rows. → individual

COUNT(column) counts only _______ values. → non-null

SUM ignores _______ values. → null

AVG ignores _______ values. → null

GROUP BY can have _______ columns. → multiple

HAVING filters based on _______ functions. → aggregate

Aggregate functions return _______ value per group. → one

ORDER BY can be used after _______ and _______. → GROUP BY, HAVING

COUNT(*) counts _______ rows including nulls. → all

SUM(column) returns the _______ of the column. → total

AVG(column) returns the _______ of the column. → average

MIN(column) returns the _______ value. → minimum

MAX(column) returns the _______ value. → maximum

Short Answer (10)

Define aggregate functions. → Functions that perform calculations on a set of rows and return a single value.

What is COUNT()? → Counts rows or non-null values.

What is SUM()? → Adds numeric values.

What is AVG()? → Returns average of numeric values.

Difference between WHERE and HAVING? → WHERE filters rows before grouping; HAVING filters groups after aggregation.

What is GROUP BY used for? → Groups rows with same values in one or more columns.

Example use of MIN/MAX. → Finding lowest/highest salary in a department.

Why use aggregate functions? → To summarize or analyze data quickly.

Difference between COUNT() and COUNT(column)? → COUNT() counts all rows; COUNT(column) counts non-null values.

Can aggregate functions be combined? → Yes, e.g., SUM and AVG together in SELECT.







4️⃣ SUBQUERIES – Questions & Answers
True/False (20)

A subquery is a query inside another query. (True)

Correlated subqueries depend on the outer query. (True)

Non-correlated subqueries are independent of outer query. (True)

Subqueries can be used in SELECT, WHERE, or FROM. (True)

EXISTS is often used with subqueries. (True)

Subqueries cannot return multiple rows. (False)

Correlated subqueries are evaluated for each row of outer query. (True)

Subqueries can filter data using IN. (True)

Subqueries cannot calculate MAX or AVG. (False)

Subqueries are always faster than JOINs. (False)

Non-correlated subqueries execute once. (True)

Correlated subqueries execute multiple times. (True)

Subqueries can be used in ORDER BY. (True)

Subqueries cannot be nested. (False)

EXISTS checks for presence of rows in a subquery. (True)

Subqueries are not useful for filtering. (False)

Subqueries can return a single value or multiple values. (True)

Correlated subqueries cannot reference outer query columns. (False)

Non-correlated subqueries are reusable. (True)

Subqueries are only used with numeric columns. (False)

Gap Filling (20)

A _______ is a query inside another query. → subquery

Subqueries in WHERE filter _______ rows. → outer

Correlated subqueries depend on _______ query. → outer

Non-correlated subqueries are _______ of outer query. → independent

Subqueries can be used in SELECT, WHERE, or _______. → FROM

EXISTS checks for _______ in a subquery. → existence of rows

Correlated subqueries execute _______ for each outer row. → repeatedly

Non-correlated subqueries execute _______ times. → once

Subqueries can calculate _______ values like MAX or AVG. → aggregate

Subqueries can return _______ or multiple values. → single

Subqueries can be nested _______ levels. → multiple

Correlated subqueries reference _______ query columns. → outer

Non-correlated subqueries are _______ reusable. → more

Subqueries are useful for _______ filtering. → conditional

IN operator can use _______ for comparison. → subquery

Subqueries can also be used in _______ clause. → ORDER BY

Subqueries are not restricted to _______ columns. → numeric

EXISTS returns _______ or _______. → TRUE, FALSE

Subqueries can simplify _______ queries. → complex

Subqueries can be combined with _______ functions. → aggregate

Short Answer (10)

Define subquery. → A query inside another query, used to filter, calculate, or compare data.

Difference between correlated and non-correlated subqueries. → Correlated depends on outer query; non-correlated does not.

Where can subqueries be used? → SELECT, WHERE, FROM clauses.

What is the purpose of EXISTS? → Checks if subquery returns rows.

Give an example use of subquery with IN. → Finding students enrolled in courses.

How does a correlated subquery execute? → For each row of the outer query.

Can subqueries return multiple values? → Yes, if using IN or EXISTS.

Can subqueries calculate aggregates? → Yes, MAX, MIN, AVG, SUM, etc.

Why use subqueries instead of JOINs sometimes? → For filtering, modular queries, or when JOINs are complex.

Can subqueries be nested multiple levels? → Yes.
